[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/bTtx3vLh/Al4AeKgG"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/A_Dragon_Riding_King"]
[UTCDate "2023.10.21"]
[UTCTime "00:29:07"]

{ Hello and welcome to my study on the Benoni. The following 40ish chapters are all variations, lines, gambits, etc. Following the variation chapters will follow games from GMs, so stick around. You will, or ought to, notice that many of the chapters are similar, this is because I copied pgn from lichess opening tree to get ALL the variations, and consequently, all includes some look-likes.

Most of the variations look like their main line, knowing all the names and moves is not necessary unless you are titled. Knowing the main structures will probably be more beneficial for you than trying to remember all the side nooks and crannies.

Furthermore, this study will not be addressing the famous Benko Gambit. There are many studies on it out there, so you will not find it here.

1.d4 }
1. d4 { The Benoni is a Defense used by Black against the move 1.d4
There are two ways to reach the Benoni, the first is playing 1...c5 right away. } 1... c5 { According to the Lichess Opening Explorer this is the Old Benoni https://lichess.org/study/Uq7jI7Nk, and is rarely played these days. Although white can take the pawn in this "gambit". Just like in the Queen's Gambit, there is no way to hang onto the pawn. More on this later. } (1... Nf6 { The second way to reach the Benoni starts with 1...Nf6 } 2. c4 { Likely anticipating one of the Indian Defenses, you can surprise your opponent with a direct c5! } 2... c5 { Seeing as you need to play c5 at some point in MOST 1.d4 openings, why not now? ;) }) 2. dxc5 e6 (2... Qa5+ 3. Nc3 Qxc5 { Also an option. }) 3. Be3 (3. b4 a5 4. a3 (4. c3 axb4 5. cxb4 Qf6 { And white must give up a minor piece to save the rook. }) 4... axb4 { [%cal Ga8a1] }) 3... Qa5+ 4. Nc3 Bxc5 { These lines are just to show how to retake if White is crazy enough to try to keep the pawn. } 5. Bxc5 Qxc5 $10 { https://lichess.org/opening/Benoni_Defense I will try to cross-reference this study to other chapters in this study, other studies, or other sources. } *


